cs.CR, cs.LG, cs.DS, cs.IT, cs.DB

This paper is likely to belong to the category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as it deals with achieving differential privacy, which is a privacy-preserving technique used in cryptography and security. It could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as differential privacy is often used in machine learning to protect sensitive data. Additionally, the paper's focus on empirical noise in the data could place it in the categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DB (Databases), as these fields often deal with data analysis and privacy. Finally, the paper's use of information theory could place it in the category of cs.IT (Information Theory).
